0.12% incidence is actually not that small. Keep in mind that's with all the precautionary measures in place. That's approximately 1 in in every 1000 people. 

The R0 (basic reproduction factor) for coronavirus is estimated around 2.5. This means *roughly* 2.5 people will be infected by every person who is already infected. So with no precautions at this R0, that 0.12% becomes 0.3% with one generation of infection. That becomes 0.75% in the second generation, and ramps up exponentially until saturation of the vulnerable population. Each of these generations seems to take ~1 week or so based on the incubation period and contagious period. This also assumes that people are completely cured within one generation, which may not be true, and they may remain infectious continuing into further generations, which would only increase the rate of infected people.

It should be mentioned that the R0 can be significantly changed by human behavior. This R0 is measured with the current reaction in place. With a loosening of restrictions it could tick upwards.

The chances are that within a couple of weeks you will probably interact with someone who has the virus. If you only interact with 2 new people daily (very conservative estimate), that's 14 people a week. In one month you're getting to roughly 60 people. In one month assuming a constant R0 and generational period of 1 week, you have a case rate of 4.69%, or roughly 1 in 21 people. So there's a good chance within a month That you'd be interacting with 3 infected people.
